JOHANNESBURG - Transformation in corporate South Africa remains extremely slow. The latest report reveals that whites and males occupy the majority of top management positions. READ: Whites still on top The Commission for Employment Equity’s annual report shows that 67.7 percent of top management positions are held by Whites. While Black South Africans only account for 14 percent. READ: Radical economic transformation about entrepreneurship: Mkhize The commission says there has been a 20 percent decrease in white management. This is still considered to be a very slow rate of transformation. Women at senior management level has increased by 18.8 percent. eNCA